[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Each chunk is preceded by its size in bytes and transmission ends when a zero-length chunk is received.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] The *chunked* keyword in the Transfer-Encoding header is used to indicate chunked transfer.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Chunked transfer encoding is not supported in HTTP/2, which provides its own mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] This transfer encoding method also allows additional entity header fields to be sent after the last chunk if the client specified the "trailers" parameter as an argument of the TE request field.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] The origin server of the response can also decide to send additional entity trailers even if the client did not specify the "trailers" parameter, but only if the metadata is optional (i.e. the client can use the received entity without them).
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Whenever the trailers are used, the server should list their names in the Trailer header field; three header field types are specifically prohibited from appearing as a trailer field: Content-Length, Trailer, and Transfer-Encoding.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Each chunk starts with the number of octets of the data it embeds expressed as a hexadecimal number in ASCII followed by optional parameters (*chunk extension*) and a terminating ␍␊ sequence, followed by the chunk data.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] If chunk extensions are provided, the chunk size is terminated by a semicolon and followed by the parameters, each also delimited by semicolons.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Each parameter is encoded as an extension name followed by an optional equal sign and value.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] These parameters could be used for a running message digest or digital signature, or to indicate an estimated transfer progress, for instance.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] The terminating chunk is a special chunk of zero length.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] It may contain a trailer, which consists of a (possibly empty) sequence of entity header fields.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Normally, such header fields would be sent in the message's header; however, it may be more efficient to determine them after processing the entire message entity.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] In that case, it is useful to send those headers in the trailer.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Header fields that regulate the use of trailers are *Transfer-Encoding* with the "trailers" parameter (used in requests) and *Trailer* (used in responses).
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] HTTP servers often use compression to optimize transmission, for example with Content-Encoding: gzip or Content-Encoding: deflate.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] If both compression and chunked encoding are enabled, then the content stream is first compressed, then chunked; so the chunk encoding itself is not compressed, and the data in each chunk is compressed holistically (i.e. based on the whole content).
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] The remote endpoint then decodes the stream by concatenating the chunks and decompressing the result.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] The following example contains three chunks of size 4, 7, and 11 (hexadecimal "B") octets of data.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Below is an annotated version of the encoded data.
[src:http-request-smuggling/chunked-transfer-encoding] Note: Each chunk's size excludes the two ␍␊ bytes that terminate the data of each chunk.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] HTTP Headers are a great booster for web security with easy implementation.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Proper HTTP response headers can help prevent security vulnerabilities like Cross-Site Scripting, Clickjacking, Information disclosure and more.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] In this cheat sheet, we will review all security-related HTTP headers, recommended configurations, and reference other sources for complicated headers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Frame-Options` HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page in a `<frame>`, `<iframe>`, `<embed>` or `<object>`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Sites can use this to avoid clickjacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy (CSP) frame-ancestors directive obsoletes X-Frame-Options for supporting browsers (source).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] X-Frame-Options header is only useful when the HTTP response where it is included has something to interact with (e.g. links, buttons).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If the HTTP response is a redirect or an API returning JSON data, X-Frame-Options does not provide any security.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Use Content Security Policy (CSP) frame-ancestors directive if possible.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Do not allow displaying of the page in a frame.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `X-XSS-Protection` response header is a feature of Internet Explorer, Chrome, and Safari that stops pages from loading when they detect reflected cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] WARNING: Even though this header can protect users of older web browsers that don't yet support CSP, in some cases, this header can create XSS vulnerabilities in otherwise safe websites source.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Use a Content Security Policy (CSP) that disables the use of inline JavaScript.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Do not set this header or explicitly turn it off.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Please see Mozilla X-XSS-Protection for details.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Content-Type-Options` response HTTP header is used by the server to indicate to the browsers that the MIME types advertised in the Content-Type headers should be followed and not guessed.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header is used to block browsers' MIME type sniffing, which can transform non-executable MIME types into executable MIME types (MIME Confusion Attacks).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Set the Content-Type header correctly throughout the site.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Referrer-Policy` HTTP header controls how much referrer information (sent via the Referer header) should be included with requests.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Referrer policy has been supported by browsers since 2014.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Today, the default behavior in modern browsers is to no longer send all referrer information (origin, path, and query string) to the same site but to only send the origin to other sites.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] However, since not all users may be using the latest browsers we suggest forcing this behavior by sending this header on all responses.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Content-Type` representation header is used to indicate the original media type of the resource (before any content encoding is applied for sending).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If not set correctly, the resource (e.g. an image) may be interpreted as HTML, making XSS vulnerabilities possible.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Although it is recommended to always set the `Content-Type` header correctly, it would constitute a vulnerability only if the content is intended to be rendered by the client and the resource is untrusted (provided or modified by a user).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Cache-Control` header defines how responses are cached by browsers and intermediate caches.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These directives help reduce the risk of sensitive data being stored or exposed through caching, but use `no-store` when storage of sensitive data must be strictly prevented.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Strict-Transport-Security` response header (often abbreviated as HSTS) instructs browsers to only access the website using HTTPS, even if a user attempts to connect over HTTP.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Please check out HTTP Strict Transport Security Cheat Sheet for more information.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Expect-CT` header lets sites opt-in to reporting of Certificate Transparency (CT) requirements.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Given that mainstream clients now require CT qualification, the only remaining value is reporting such occurrences to the nominated report-uri value in the header.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The header is now less about enforcement and more about detection/reporting.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Mozilla recommends avoiding it, and removing it from existing code if possible.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy (CSP) is a security feature that is used to specify the origin of content that is allowed to be loaded on a website or in a web application.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement to distribution of malware.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Content Security Policy is complex to configure and maintain.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you don't use this header, your site is protected by default by the Same Origin Policy (SOP).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] What this header does is relax this control in specified circumstances.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` is a CORS (cross-origin resource sharing) header.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header indicates whether the response it is related to can be shared with requesting code from the given origin.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] In other words, if siteA requests a resource from siteB, siteB should indicate in its `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header that siteA is allowed to fetch that resource, if not, the access is blocked due to Same Origin Policy (SOP).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you use it, set specific origins instead of `*`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Check out Access-Control-Allow-Origin for details.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy` (COOP) response header allows you to ensure a top-level document does not share a browsing context group with cross-origin documents.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This header works together with Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy (COEP) and Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy (CORP) explained below.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This mechanism protects against attacks like Spectre which can cross the security boundary established by Same Origin Policy (SOP) for resources in the same browsing context group.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] As these headers are very related to browsers, it may not make sense to be applied to REST APIs or clients that are not browsers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Isolates the browsing context exclusively to same-origin documents.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy` (COEP) response header prevents a document from loading any cross-origin resources that don't explicitly grant the document permission (using CORP or CORS).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] A document can only load resources from the same origin, or resources explicitly marked as loadable from another origin.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy` (CORP) header allows you to control the set of origins that are empowered to include a resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It is a robust defense against attacks like Spectre, as it allows browsers to block a given response before it enters an attacker's process.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Limit current resource loading to the site and sub-domains only.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Permissions-Policy allows you to control which origins can use which browser features, both in the top-level page and in embedded frames.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] For every feature controlled by Feature Policy, the feature is only enabled in the current document or frame if its origin matches the allowed list of origins.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This means that you can configure your site to never allow the camera or microphone to be activated.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This prevents that an injection, for example an XSS, enables the camera, the microphone, or other browser feature.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] FLoC is a method proposed by Google in 2021 to deliver interest-based advertisements to groups of users ("cohorts").
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, Mozilla, and others believe FLoC does not do enough to protect users' privacy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] A site can declare that it does not want to be included in the user's list of sites for cohort calculation by sending this HTTP header.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `Server` header describes the software used by the origin server that handled the request — that is, the server that generated the response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This is not a security header, but how it is used is relevant for security.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Remove this header or set non-informative values.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-Powered-By` header describes the technologies used by the webserver.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] This information exposes the server to attackers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Using the information in this header, attackers can find vulnerabilities easier.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Provides information about the .NET version.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Add the following line in your `web.config` in the `<system.web>` section to remove it.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] To remove the `X-AspNetMvc-Version` header, add the below line in `Global.asax` file.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `X-Robots-Tag` response header controls how search engines and other automated crawlers index and display resources such as PDFs, images, and other non-HTML content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It functions similarly to the `<meta name="robots">` tag, but is applied via the HTTP response header, allowing greater flexibility (e.g., for non-HTML files or server-wide rules).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] You can also use other directives such as `noarchive`, `nosnippet`, or `noimageindex` depending on your needs.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Server configuration can apply this header selectively — for example, only on specific file types (like PDFs or images).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-DNS-Prefetch-Control` HTTP response header controls DNS prefetching, a feature by which browsers proactively perform domain name resolution on both links that the user may choose to follow as well as URLs for items referenced by the document, including images, CSS, JavaScript, and so forth.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The default behavior of browsers is to perform DNS caching which is good for most websites.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you do not control links on your website, you might want to set `off` as a value to disable DNS prefetch to avoid leaking information to those domains.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Public-Key-Pins` response header was used to associate a specific cryptographic public key with a web server to mitigate MITM attacks with forged certificates.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It was removed from Chromium in 2018 and is unsupported by all modern browsers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Remove any `Public-Key-Pins` or `Public-Key-Pins-Report-Only` headers from production.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Rely on Certificate Transparency (CT) and CAA DNS records, which provide superior compromise detection without the operational brittleness of pinning.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] When serving user-provided files, proper HTTP headers should be used to prevent unintended execution in the browser.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These headers help reduce risks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and unintended file execution.
