[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The Mozilla Observatory is an online tool which helps you to check your website's header status.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] SmartScanner has a dedicated test profile for testing security of HTTP headers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Online tools usually test the homepage of the given address.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] But SmartScanner scans the whole website.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-headers-cheat-sheet] So, you can make sure all of your web pages have the right HTTP Headers in place.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Under HTTP 1.0, connections should always be **closed** by the server after sending the response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Since at least late 1995, developers of popular products (browsers, web servers, etc.) using HTTP/1.0, started to add an unofficial extension (to the protocol) named "keep-alive" in order to allow the reuse of a connection for multiple requests/responses.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] When the server receives this request and generates a response, if it supports keep-alive then it also adds the same above header to the response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Following this, the connection is not dropped, but is instead kept open.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] When the client sends another request, it uses the same connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] After that the connection is closed following specified rules.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Since 1997, the various versions of HTTP/1.1 specifications acknowledged the usage of this unofficial extension and included a few caveats regarding the interoperability between HTTP/1.0 (keep-alive) and HTTP/1.1 clients / servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] In HTTP 1.1, all connections are considered persistent unless declared otherwise.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] The HTTP **persistent connections** do not use separate keepalive messages, they just allow multiple requests to use a single connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] However, the default connection timeout of Apache httpd 1.3 and 2.0 is as little as 15 seconds and just 5 seconds for Apache httpd 2.2 and above.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] The advantage of a short timeout is the ability to deliver multiple components of a web page quickly while not consuming resources to run multiple server processes or threads for too long.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Keepalive makes it difficult for the client to determine where one response ends and the next response begins, particularly during pipelined HTTP operation.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] This is a serious problem when `Content-Length` cannot be used due to streaming.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] To solve this problem, HTTP 1.1 introduced a chunked transfer coding that defines a `last-chunk` bit.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] The `last-chunk` bit is set at the end of each response so that the client knows where the next response begins.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] According to RFC 7230, section 6.4, "a client ought to limit the number of simultaneous open connections that it maintains to a given server".
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] The previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification stated specific maximum values but in the words of RFC 7230 "this was found to be impractical for many applications... instead... be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] These guidelines are intended to improve HTTP response times and avoid congestion.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] If HTTP pipelining is correctly implemented, there is no performance benefit to be gained from additional connections, while additional connections may cause issues with congestion.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] If the client does not close the connection when all of the data it needs has been received, the resources needed to keep the connection open on the server will be unavailable for other clients.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] This affects both server's availability and the availability of resources on the server, with the degree of impact depending on the server's architecture and configuration.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Also a race condition can occur where the client sends a request to the server at the same time that the server closes the TCP connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] A server should send a 408 Request Timeout status code to the client immediately before closing the connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] When a client receives the 408 status code, after having sent the request, it may open a new connection to the server and re-send the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Not all clients will re-send the request, and many that do will only do so if the request has an idempotent HTTP method.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] All modern web browsers including Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Opera (since 4.0), and Safari use persistent connections.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] In Firefox, the number of simultaneous connections can be customized (per-server, per-proxy, total).
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Persistent connections time out after 115 seconds (1.92 minutes) of inactivity which is changeable via the configuration.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-persistent-connection] Python's `requests` library contains `requests.Session()`, which establishes a persistent HTTP connection, thereby allowing the underlying TCP connection to be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] The Transfer-Encoding header works by defining a directive on how to interpret the body of the HTTP request, with the common and necessary directive for this attack being the chunked transfer encoding.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] When the Transfer-Encoding header is present, the Content-Length header is supposed to be omitted.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Working similarly but with a different syntax, the Content-Length header works by specifying the size in bytes of the body as a value in the header itself.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Vulnerabilities arise when both of these headers are included in a malicious HTTP request, bypassing security functions meant to prevent malicious HTTP queries to the server by causing either the front-end or back-end server to incorrectly interpret the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end processes the request using Content-Length header while backend processes the request using Transfer-Encoding header.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] The attack would be carried out with the first part of the request declaring a zero length chunk.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] The front end server seeing this would only read the first part of the request and unintentionally pass the second part to the back end server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Once passed through to the back end server, it would be treated as the next request and processed, carrying out the attackers hidden request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end processes request using Transfer-Encoding header while backend processes the request using Content-Length header.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] In this attack, a hacker would declare the valid length of the first chunk, which houses the malicious request and then declare a second chunk with a length of 0.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] When the front end server sees the second chunk with a length of 0 it believes the request to be complete and passes it along to the back end server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] The back end server processes the request using the Content-Length header, however, and as a result the malicious request left in the first chunk go unprocessed until they are treating as being at the start of next request in the sequence and are carried out.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] In this type of HTTP request smuggling, the front end and backend both process the request using Transfer-Encoding header, but the header can be obfuscated in a way (for example by nonstandard whitespace formatting or duplicate headers) that makes one of the servers but not the other one ignore it.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Obscuring the header may take the form of adding in an incorrect character, such as Transfer-Encoding: xchunked, or an unusual new line character between 'Transfer-Encoding' and ': chunked'.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] If one of the front of back end servers still processes these obfuscated HTTP requests, then the rest of the attack will be similar to how CL.TE or TE.CL attacks work.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] The best prevention to these attacks would clearly be if frontend and backend servers interpreted HTTP requests the same way.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] However, this is usually not an option as load balancers support backend servers run on distinct platforms, using different software.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Most variants of this attack can be prevented by using HTTP/2, as it uses a different method to determine the length of a request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Another method of avoiding the attack is for the frontend server to normalize HTTP requests before passing them to the backend, ensuring that they get interpreted in the same way.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] Configuring a web application firewall is another good way to prevent HRS attacks as many feature technology that identify attack attempts and either blocks or sanitize the suspicious incoming requests.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] (2021) found that most front-end web servers (e.g. proxy servers) provided the parsing features for hindering in practice, all the known HRS attacks on the back-end web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/http-request-smuggling] (2022) proposed a method using Flask so to implement suitable parsing features that prevent HRS attacks, from a front-end program or web server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:http-request-smuggling/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:http-request-smuggling/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:http-request-smuggling/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
